attributes.magic: ELF 32-bit LSB executable, MIPS, MIPS-I version 1 (SYSV), statically linked, stripped

threat_severity.level_description: Severity HIGH because it was considered trojan. Other contributing factor was that it could not be run in sandboxes.

crowdsourced_yara_results.description: Detects suspicious single byte XORed keyword 'Mozilla/5.0' - it uses yara's XOR modifier and therefore cannot print the XOR key. You can use the CyberChef recipe linked in the reference field to brute force the used key.
crowdsourced_yara_results.author: Florian Roth

crowdsourced_ai_results.analysis: The binary is a DDoS bot. It makes extensive use of networking syscalls (`socket`, `connect`, `sendto`, `recvfrom`) to craft and send packets, indicative of network flooding capabilities. It contains numerous heavily obfuscated strings to hide configuration and C2 information, a common malware evasion technique. The presence of `http/1.1` suggests C2 communication over HTTP. Additionally, it uses `fork` and redirects I/O to `/dev/null`, which are standard techniques for daemonization to run persistently in the background.
